[5] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Mon 16 Sep 2013
Source: The Brisbane Times [edited]
http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/new-measles-case-confirmed-in-queensland-20130916-2tu7t.html


Queenslanders are being urged to check their measles vaccination records, following the 14th diagnosis of the highly infectious disease in the state this year [2013].

In the past 2 weeks alone, 5 people in Ipswich have been diagnosed with measles. A range of interstate and international visitors have also been diagnosed while visiting the state's southeast in the past 2 months.

Queensland Health communicable diseases unit doctor Stephen Lambert urged those aged 30 to 45 to check their vaccination records, saying the group was more susceptible to the disease than other parts of the population: "This group, now aged about 30 to 45 years, were young children during the years when vaccine was 1st being used in Australia, but uptake was low. Even low vaccine uptake had a quick effect on dampening down measles virus circulation, meaning that this group of children didn't catch measles infection and may not have been immunised. This has left them vulnerable to catching measles when exposed." The health authority said anyone concerned should see their GP immediately to discuss their options.

Measles vaccinations were introduced in 1966, and since then, the number of cases has fallen dramatically. Public health staff around the southeast are working to ascertain the links, if there are any, between the recent cases.

The 1st case in the most recent outbreak of measles was confirmed in Queensland in late July 2013, when a Victorian who had contracted the disease following an outbreak in that state visited Brisbane while unknowingly infectious. A 2nd infected Victorian travelled extensively on the city's public transport network between 9-17 Aug 2013, while an international tourist travelled from Cairns to Brisbane and then on to Sydney between 16-24 Aug 2013. A Caboolture High School student was diagnosed in late August 2013, while the 1st Ipswich case came in early September 2013.

Dr Lambert advised anyone in Brisbane between these dates to be on the lookout for symptoms of the disease. "True measles is a serious viral infection that causes fever, cough, runny nose, then a red spotty rash and sore eyes a few days later," he said. "Measles occasionally has dangerous complications with up to 1/3rd of young adults with measles ending up being treated in hospital."

He said that anybody who had or knew someone with those symptoms should visit their GP immediately.

--
